üáÆüá™üáÆüá™üáÆüá™ The Republic of Ireland, known as the home of Guinness Beer, is a country with rich history, magical landscape, crowded Irish pubs and well-preserved castles. Like other countries, Ireland is still fighting with the coronavirus. This blog will analyse Ireland‚Äôs coronavirus situation on diffent aspect including demographic aspects (age, gender). We will look at the population and total confirmed cases of each county in Ireland, confirmed covid cases base on age groups, gender and many others.

Data Description üìñ

Data Source

The data source for the this blog is from Ireland‚Äôs COVID-19 Data Hub. Three data sets are selected from this website. The first dataste is the Covid-19 County Statistics HPSC Ireland Open Data which allows me to make visualisation of the confirmed cases in each county. Next, the Covid-19 County Statistics HPSC Ireland allows me to make time-series visualisation using the timestamps provided. Lastly, the Covid Statistics Profile HPSC Ireland Open Data allows me to analyse and draw maps related to the covid data with demographic variables.

Findings üîç

Overview of population and COVID-19 cases

Table 1 shows the population proportion covid cases and population from Census 2016 in each county in The Republic of Ireland. Data for the 26 counties are recorded. We can see that Dublin, the capital city of Ireland, has an approximately 9353 population proportion covid cases while the population recorded on Census 2016 was 1347359, which was the county with the highest population nationwide. Next, we can see that Cork has the second highest number of population recorded on the Census 2016 with a total of 542868 and has an approximately 5835 population proportion covid cases recorded.

The map below allows us to identify the spread of Coronavirus throughout the whole nation by showing the total confirmed covid cases in Ireland. We can see that the distribution of covid cases across Ireland are very diverse as some county has total confirmed cases recorded of more than 100,000 cases while some county has total of 0 - 2000 confirmed cases recorded. From the map provided below, we can see that Dublin has become a covid hotspot by having the highest number of total confirmed covid cases, which is 126781 cases. Despite of population factor, we could assume that Dublin has more international travellers and the government has failures in hotel quarantine and there could be more high risk venues in the capital city such as school, pubs and shopping malls.

On the other hand, we can see that Leitrim has a total of 1599 confirmed covid cases, which is the covid safest county among others. Opposite to Dublin, Leitrim has the least number of population recorded from Census 2016 in Ireland. We can assume that there is not much high risk venues and activities in Leitrim and people over there are more aware of the coronavirus.

Next, readers are able to select and compare the confirmed covid cases in each county in Ireland throughout the time period.

New cases and new deaths throughout the time-series

According to Figure 3 above, the orange time series line shwos the confirmed covid cases and the blue line shows the confirmed covid deaths in Ireland from March 2020 to September 2021. First and foremost, the most surprising point, the confirmed covid cases skyrocketed from the end of December and reaches it‚Äôs peak on 7 of January 2021. Ireland achieved a total of 8348 confirmed covid cases and 20 confirmed covid deaths on 7 January 2021. In my opinion, people in Ireland could got infected due to the celebration of Christmas and New Year. There could be crowds celebrating festivals in public and disobeying the covid rules which will help in preventing infection. Thus, as it takes around 2 weeks to show symptoms of the Coronavirus, people remain unaware and did not quarantine and therefore infect others. This could be the reason causing the serious outbreak in January 2021. At the end of January 2021, the total confirmed covid cases in Ireland started to decrease and did not exceed 1000 cases each day. Perhaps the government has imposed a lockdown or other rules to stop this outbreak. Next, starting from the mid of July, the trend of confirmed covid cases in Ireland started to rise again and has reaches it‚Äôs peak in the mid of August and started to decrease. In my opinion, this peak could be caused by the Delta variant outbreak, which is twice as contagious as the previous variant.

Demographic (Gender)

According to the pie chart above, we can see that 51.2% of confirmed covid cases in Ireland are Female patients and 48.7% of confirmed covid cases in Ireland are Male. Both gender shares a very similar of proportion of covid cases in Ireland. Besides that, 0.0395% of covid patient‚Äôs gender in Ireland remained Unknown.

Demographic (Age Groups)

Figure 1: The distribution of Covid cases across each age groups

According to the figure above showing the distribution of covid cases across each age groups, we can see that Aged 15 to 24 is the age group with the highest number of confirmed cases (78361) in Ireland. Next, followed by Aged 25 to 34, Aged 35 to 44 and Aged 45 to 54, which respectively has 64610, 56105 and 47619 confirmed cases within the age group. Moreover, we can see that Aged 5 to 14 (35850) and Aged 55 to 64 (33924) has very similar number of confirmed covid cases. Last but not least, Aged 65 to 74 has a total of 16790 confirmed covid cases, Aged 1 to 4 has a total of 14348 confirmed covid cases while Aged 85 up has the least total of confirmed covid cases with a sum of 8337 among other age groups.

Hospitalised, Healthcare Workers and ICU required COVID-19 cases

Moving to the very last graph, the interactive graph above shows the record of hospitalised covid cases, health care workers covid cases and covid cases that requires ICU in Ireland. We can see that the health care workers covid cases are basically more than hospitalised covid cases and covid cases that requires ICU especially for the first peak at April 2020 and the secod peak at January 2021. In my opinion, the first peak of health care workers covid cases could be cause by the initial COVID 19 outbreak, there could be limited amount of personal protective equipments for health care workers causing health care workers especially frontliners having greater risk of getting infected by others. As mentioned previously, the second peak for these three variables could be caused by celebrating Christmas and New Year. The more confirmed covid cases, the more hospitalised covid cases and more covid cases requiring ICU will be and will put health care workers at higher risk. However, the trend of confirming covid cases for health care workers seems to decreases significantly after the second peak and has remain stable at a very small amount. In my opinion, this could be most of the health care workers are vaccinated. Thus, the amount of health care workers covid cases normally has a positive linear relationship with the total confirmed cases and hospitalised covid cases, however, the hospitalised workers covid cases does not seem to increase while the amount of hospitalised covid cases increased after July 2021.
